'''Lancepesade''' derives from the [[Italian language|Italian]] ''lanzia spezzata'', which literally means "broken lance" or "broken spear", but which was used to denote a seasoned soldier (the broken spear being a metaphor for combat experience, where such an occurrence was likely).

Initially lancepesade was considered a grade within the [[Private (rank)|rank of private]]&ndash;lancepesades were either assigned as assistants to corporals or performed the duties of corporals themselves. As a result of this second role, lancepesade was increasingly considered a grade within the rank of corporal; as a result, lancepesades were referred to as lance corporals. (Lance Corporal was derived from combining lancepesade and corporal.)

